				\begin{document}$$ \uppi = \mathrm{P}\left(\mathrm{D} = 1\right) = \left(\mathrm{T}\mathrm{P} + \mathrm{F}\mathrm{N}\right)/\left(\mathrm{T}\mathrm{P} + \mathrm{F}\mathrm{P} + \mathrm{F}\mathrm{N} + \mathrm{T}\mathrm{N}\right) $$\end{document}π=PD=1=TP+FN/TP+FP+FN+TNwhere: π is the true prevalence, P is the apparent prevalence, D is the status of infection, TP is true positive, FN is false negative, FP is false positive, and TN is true negative.

Microscopy analysis revealed the presence of haemosporidian parasites in samples of two bird species, house finches and canyon towhees, whereas in cactus wren samples, only normal erythrocytes were observed. As is typical of the life-cycle of Haemoproteus spp., the asexual stages of these parasites, microgametocytes and macrogametocytes, within erythrocytes from infected birds were observed in most of our samples (Fig. 2). On the other hand, no meronts of Plasmodium were detected in red blood cells, but the presence of Plasmodium was evidenced by PCR amplification in two birds. Haemosporidian prevalence was 47.5 % for the canyon towhee, and 44.3 % for the house finch (Table 1).Fig. 2
